Aug 24 2009 	Cute but broken	Just returned from a stay at the Tomo. It was both good and bad, hence the middling rating.It's obviously an older best western re-done in a cute J-Pop style. The bedrooms themselves are funky and bright in an Ikea-meets-Japan sort of way. Very clean. Although, for reasons I can't understand, someone thought painting a windowless interior bathroom dark grey and adding an opaque dark gray shower curtain and installing a single low wattage florescent bulb was a good idea. Unless you're a fan of prisons, it wasn't. However, the shower had good water pressure and lots of hot water. Beds, linens, and towels and such were all of the quality I would expect of a mid-priced hotel.When we first checked in at the front desk in the late afternoon, the desk clerk was indifferent. He gave us the key card and we headed up to the room only to discover it wasn't what we had booked. We'd paid for an upgrade to a upper room with a balcony. So we schlep back downstairs. He gives us another room key to the right room. It was a very long traveling day so we decide to just get snacks at the market (nice to have one nearby!) and settle in for evening of being couch potatoes and watching pay-per-view.Except the pay per view movies didn't work. We call down stairs to inquire what the problem could be. Mr. Personality at the desk says he doesn't know, and &quot;I don’t know what to tell you.&quot; When we indicate that it's really kinda his job to know these things, he tells us his colleague who actually knows something about the hotel systems will be in a half hour. As promised, a half hour or so later, the competent employee shows up. He fiddles with the cable box, indicates that it is indeed broken and offers to move us to yet another room. So we switch rooms for a third time. In fairness, the nighttime employee was very helpful and accommodating, he apologized, brought a cart to tote the luggage and gave us a free pass for a couple breakfasts at the hotel dining room. That was nice, considering the day-shift guy's attitude was &quot;hey, sucks to be you.&quot;While the hotel offers free wireless, forget actually trying to use it for more than a couple minutes at a time. It's intermittent at best and drops out constantly. They outsource the service and it took multiple phone calls to get the service running. Even with help, it's not consistent. If you actually plan on doing some work, you will be frustrated.The next day, again, we come back to the room that night to find that TV and lamp in the desk area isn't working. We fiddle with the surge protector under the desk to no avail. We call down. Guy comes up. Apparently the surge protector has to be &quot;jiggled&quot; just right in the outlet. I can only guess that the maid accidently unjiggled it while sweeping. (frankly the wiring and multiple extension cords all looked like a fire waiting to happen) On the day we left, we went to the house computers to print out our boarding passes. Attached to both the computers were &quot;out of order signs&quot; indicating that they wouldn't be fixed until the next day. The woman at the desk was nice enough to log on and print out the passes. That evening, I I had to go to three different floors to find a coke machine that actually worked. No exaggeration.So we met two very good employees and one very indifferent one. The room was nice, the bathroom was creepy and there were multiple issues with the amenities. The front desk did eventually make some monetary adjustments for all of the inconveniences, and that was nice, of course. I don't expect perfection, but I do expect problems to be corrected, alleviated, or compensated, which eventually they were. But equally, they would not have had to make such concessions IF items just worked as they are intended to in the first place. While the hotel is cute and it's in a nice location, but they really need to put some money into their infrastructure. I'd still recommend it as we seemed to have a run of bad luck, but if you're not a patient person, you might want to look elsewhere.	
Aug 1 2009 	Fun stylish hotel at decent price	This sad, old hotel on the edge of calm Japantown and trendy Pacific Heights got a great make-over. The theme is &quot;mod&quot; Japanese. Rooms: huge (many have spectacular views); terrific beds; small refrigerators; safes for valuables; immaculate. Nearby: dozens of Japanese restaurants and shops (try Genji's for antiques or the two-floor bookstore), the Sundance movie theaters and Kabuki Hot Springs spa; Japanese grocery store with delicious, fresh meals to go. Ten-minute walk: Fillmore Street's trendy restaurants/shops (Dosa for amazing California-Indian food, Osaka for terrific sushi and Peet's for best coffee). Great bus service to get you around the city (no subway in this part of town). Huge Safeway 3-4 blocks away. I paid $109/night for my room. A friend paid $10/night more for his. Downside: The free wireless is awful (there are two computers in the lobby and the coffee shops on Fillmore Street all off free wireless). The parking is limited and expensive, although there's a second lot two blocks away. It's a pain to get to BART for the train to airport (although there's a $16 shuttle). Some may prefer to be down near Union Square for more mass transit and shopping options (but it's also very touristy).	
Jul 31 2009 	a little J-pop culture in San Francisco	We just got back from a one night stay at the Hotel Tomo. We had a double Queen room with balcony on the top floor, great views of San Francisco and the Peace Pagoda. The room was clean, and furnished in fun style with bright bedspreads, a cool wall mural taken from some anime movie, and even Japanese style toiletries. The staff was nice, and the parking conveniently next door to the hotel. My teenagers loved the Japanese styling and lobby videos, but I didn't see any of the game consoles I had expected. In addition the wifi was very slow, both in the rooms and in the complimentary terminals in the lobby. The gym in the hotel was tiny, a converted room I think, but had fresh air. The neighbourhood is different for San Francisco, not near the tourist attractions but very charming in its own way. I have an interest in Japanese culture, so I enjoyed the historic plaques posted on buildings as well as the Japanese mall and restaurants close by. If you walk to nearby Filmore Street, you can check out some ritzy shopping as well as the interesting architecture of Pacific Heights. And you don't see tourists everywhere as you do downtown.We stayed here one night and two in the Union Square area. I booked at the last minute and I thought that at $193 the room was a little pricey, but if you could get a better deal it would be a great place to explore a different side of San Francisco in a very fun environment.	
