Jan 17 2009 	Hotel Tomo surpassed my expectations!	I'm surprised to be writing such a stellar review for this hotel after reading many of the comments from other reviewers. I anticipated having the same problems - rude service, slamming doors, lousy wifi connection, and fickle heating. However, given the uniqueness of Hotel Tomo, I was willing to give it a shot. I honestly can say that this hotel far surpassed my expectations and catered to all of my needs for my trip (efficient service, quiet floor, clean room, cool environment). Having said this, readers should keep in mind that this hotel IS a mid-range Best Western, and is neither a five star hotel nor a hostel. You won't get room service or ear-to-ear smiles from the staff, but you needn't worry about comfort, cleanliness, or safety.The service was great - I checked in quite late without any hitches, asked directions and questions of the front desk, and requested taxis from the staff. As my return flight was at 10 pm, the staff was quite amiable about storing my luggage, and actually refused a tip upon retrieving my bags!What prompted me to give this hotel an &quot;excellent&quot; score was the fact that a personalized letter from the head housekeeper was left on my desk, and the &quot;guest experience&quot; manager left a message on my phone to call her extension if I needed anything during my stay. During my visits to much higher end hotels, I only received these types of gestures when doing business with these properties. As just a &quot;regular&quot; guest, I found their messages quite personal and reassuring. The wifi worked perfectly, as did the tea kettle, alarm clock, A/C, and in-room safe. Yuzu-bergamot toiletries and the cushy robe were nice touches, and it was nice waking up to my own music on my ipod. A printer and two computers are available in the lobby for printing out boarding passes, maps, etc.Location is a bit far from the touristy parts of SF, but dead in the heart of Japantown. It was nice to be able to grab take-out ramen from Tanpopo and be back in my room within 5 minutes. A great Korean spa is only a few minutes away as well.A few minor CONS: Housekeeping staff did come knocking at my door at 8:30 am. Fortunately, I was already up, but for those wanting to sleep late, remember to hang that &quot;Do Not Disturb&quot; sign before you turn out the lights. Free breakfast may be too much to ask for, but putting complimentary coffee/tea/fruit in the lobby would be a nice touch. Overall, I would definitely stay here again. If you're not a fan of anime or don't have a sense of humor about the Tomo's decor (i.e., you're &quot;scared&quot; of the room murals!), I would advise you to look elsewhere. For all those looking for a unique experience at a decent rate, I would recommend this place wholeheartedly.	
Jan 10 2009 	Coolest Best Western I've stayed at!	I think whoever had the idea to re-design this Best Western hotel with a &quot;Japanimation&quot; theme is a genius! I wish more small hotels in American cities would convert into art-themed hotels like the Tomo.We enjoyed the concept and the decor. The murals in the rooms and in the hotel restaurant were really cool. The vending machine in the lobby selling $35 gifts was funny, but I was too broke to partake in this.I appreciated the convenient, free internet access in the lobby.The gym had a nice view of the surrounding neighborhood of Japantown, though it was COLD in that room when I went.I took off one star because: 1) breakfast is NOT included when you book; 2) I wish the &quot;gaming rooms&quot; were open when we went so that we could enjoy the decor -- these rooms were closed when we were there; and 3) the week we were there, they did not have the free sake that they usually have for the hotel guests (for some reason, they suspended Hospitality Hour the week of Christmas).	
Dec 28 2008 	Hotel Tomo is Quirky Clean Fun!	I stayed here with my family over Christmas and completely fell in love with this little hotel! In addition to providing us with a comfortable stay in a clean room, there is character running rampant throughout this establishment. The decor is funky tech, from the anime-themed wall murals and Pac Man colors in the halls to the flat-screen TVs and iPod alarm clocks. Comfort, however, is not lost in the novelty. The beds and blankets were soft, the shower was warm and a restaurant on the second floor served a filling breakfast (they served Western egg plates as well as Japanese fish and noodle dishes). The location in Japan Town is ideal for those wanting to avoid the noisy tourist areas but still see a unique, authentic part of San Francisco with restaurants and shopping nearby. The service is not &quot;4-star&quot; - don't expect bellhops or concierge service - but neither is the price, and the people at the desk were friendly and attentive. I definitely will stay here again.	
Dec 28 2008 	Good Budget Hotel in a Good Area	This is a good budget hotel in a nice residential neighborhood. The hotel parking structure appears to hold only a few cars, so we parked in the surrounding neighborhood at night. Some streets have 2-hour parking limits starting at 8:00am, so look for the parking signs to avoid a ticket!We only wanted a decent place to sleep and shower that was located near our friend’s home, so for $99 a night we didn’t mind that the rooms were sparsely furnished and the bathroom light was very dim. The dorm-like furnishings of hard chairs and limited desk space wouldn’t be very comfortable if an adult had to work in the room, but the room was clean and a standard size. Like others, I had problems getting the TV remote to work when I pushed the buttons, but that was OK, since I didn't spend much time in the room.The dark, airless restaurant wasn’t appealing, but there are many places to eat within walking distance.This is a good hotel for the price, but don’t look for the nicer amenities found in higher priced hotels.	
