Mar 13 2008 	Hotel Tomo Just Alright	My husband and I stayed at the Hotel Tomo in early March. It was my husband's first time in San Francisco and I hadn't been since I was 10. We were very excited about our spring break getaway. I booked the hotel online through the &quot;joy of life&quot; hotels. I got a great package for $109 a night including breakfast for two. When we arrived at the hotel, the person at the front desk said they didn't honor the breakfast for two. This irked me right off, but I let it slide because I was excited about the trip. To break it down, here are the pros and cons of the Hotel Tomo:Pros:Great location. Right next to Japan Center and Fillmore Street. Lots of shopping and great restaurants. Reasonably priced.CleanPretty spacious.Elevators were quick.Cons:The bathroom. Period. The light in the bathroom was buzzing and zapping and didn't always come on. The walls in the bathroom were dark grey. Sometimes I felt like I was in a horror movie. The hot and cold were opposite of what they were labeled. The water would turn frigid or scalding hot without me touching a thing (be careful if you have little ones taking a shower without assistance!!). The toilet had such low flow I was always worried it wouldn't flush. The maids were extraordinarily loud in the morning. We were by the utility closet so I got to hear them barking orders and yelling at each other at 7 a.m. The restaurant smelled like a middle school cafeteria. There was no way I wanted to eat there. The pictures on the web were very deceiving. The website boasts in room coffee, I was sad to see it was instant. Gross. On the positive side they did offer green tea. Nice touch... The ice machine didn't work on our floor. The elevator said to go to the 4th floor for additional vending machines. I saw one and it had 70% of the items sold out.In conclusion, if you are on a budget and like Japantown you may want to stay here. If you like something a little more upscale and want more nightlife,