Mar 3 2008 	a little grim	Hotel Tomo is in a great location, if you want to thoroughly shop Japantown (my kids love Japantown). The hotel boasts a &quot;Japanese pop culture&quot; theme, but apparently Japanese pop culture is a little grim. The hotel's theme is bluegrey with the occasional bright yellow, enhanced by dim fluorescent lighting. The drawings on the walls are of faceless people being watched by storm troopers with dogs, plus the occasional weeping spirit girl. I'm sure this has appeal, but not especially to kids.I've spent a lot of time in Japan, and this hotel would really benefit from a little bona fide Japanese sense of pride. I asked the maids to remove the drippy handprints from the windows (the maids were very nice), but there was nothing I could do about the soapy, greasy, really exceptionally dirty flatware in the restaurant. The dishwasher was obviously broken but in use anyway. There were no apologies from the waiter. Because there was a storm that night, my kids rented a hotel movie. The quality was terrible- the picture jumped all around, and flashed between black and white and color. Again, the staff at the desk couldn't care less. On the plus side, the japanese breakfast in the restaurant was really quite good. However, if you want to get a Shabu dinner, I'd skip this place (which has a broken down Lyon's kind of feel, at least in the mornings)- I recommend Shabu-Sen, just a block away. The service, ambiance, and food are all terrific, and kids love cooking their own food. My girls and I also really enjoyed the Hawaiian restaurant (Honu) a block away from the hotel. They had a live band, great fries, a friendly ohana feeling, and plenty of Hawaiian beers on tap.	
