Feb 11 2008 	Not that great	I would have to agree with the previous poster regarding the service. I'm not a person who requires hotel employees to go out of their way to be friendly but no one at the front desk ever greeted me or showed any interest in me, whatsoever. They behaved so strangely, for example, when I checked in, I gave my name and the employee pulled out a piece of printed paper waved it at me as if to show me the print (which I couldn't see) and said my name aloud as if to say to me: &quot;Here, I found your paperwork!&quot;. When I checked out, the clerk assumed that the woman standing next to me was with me (she wasn't -- ok, he couldn't have known that) but after getting both our room numbers, he printed my paperwork and then turned to her to give her her paperwork. By that point, he was ignoring me. The other clerk, stood behind him watching their interaction and I had to gently flag down that person to hand my bag over to him. None of this was terrible, of course, but I've stayed at lots of JDV hotels, and the service is always top notch. I'm guessing that this hotel is not owned by JDV but is simply &quot;sold&quot; by them.I hope when the management responds to this posting that the manager discloses the hotel's relationship to JDV.On another matter, I found the room very noisy. I stayed near the elevator (and although there was a utility room between my room and the elevator), I could hear the elevator opening and closing all night (and into the early morning hours). I am not a light sleeper but I would have to say that the other guests that returned to their rooms saw no problem with talking loudly and laughing loudly as they tromped down the halls to their rooms. In addition, the doors to the rooms are on heavy springs so after being serenaded by other guests in the hallway, I got used to the loud slamming of their doors when they entered. There are also a lot of noises in the room. There is some sort of ventilation system in bathroom that you cannot control that makes a lot of noise. (I closed the door to the bathroom to lessen it). In addition, there was a refrigerator (which was empty), which turned on only once and scared the living daylights out of me. I quickly got up and turned it off.Lastly, both my friend (who stayed on the top floor near the rear of the hotel) and myself had trouble regulating the temperature in the room. The first thing you have to be aware of is that the switch marked &quot;air conditioning&quot; is both the A/C and the heat. So, if the room is cold, turn on the A/C and then set the thermostat to the temperature you want and the heat will come on. Even with the &quot;A/C&quot; turned off, one night, the room was on the warm side because, I am guessing, the person below me must have had their heat turned up high. I didn't want to turn on the real air conditioning in February just to combat the heat from downstairs so I put up with it.The hotel has a cute motif and the neighborhood is pleasant. We had a car but used public transit which was easy to access. I can't say that I would return to this hotel any time soon.	
Jan 27 2008 	Absolutely Perfect	I cannot think of any reason why anyone would be dissatisfied with this hotel. I found it clean, modern and friendly. On top of all this the price was very low. As I walked into the room I immediately felt very cheerful because of the light, bright colour scheme and the interesting mural on the wall. A lady, who I think was called Gill, who works at the front desk went out of her way to be extra helpful and friendly.One thing you should know: Tomo is not in the bustling centre of San Francisco, it's in a more residential area (I personally liked this because I always like to see how the true residents live when I visit a city). I saw a couple of other hotels in the centre and they seemed to be a lot older (old buildings, old interiors) and were, of course, hugely more expensive. In comparison, Tomo was in a lovely condition. There's a bus that stops outside the hotel and gets you to the centre in less than 10 minutes and costs $1.50.These are the only two reasons why you may not love this hotel:1. You're old and it's too 'trendy' for you.2. You want to be right in the very centre of San Francisco, ie. next to Union Square. Tip: If you stay here, turn right out of the hotel and after about 3 blocks you'll reach Fillmore street which has lovely little shops and restaurants. If you walk up Fillmore street, where it meets Broadway, there's a view of the bay and the Golden Gate Bridge. I only found all this by accident when I got off the bus at the wrong stop!And one more thing, there's cool, big beanbag in every room!	
